<ContentPage
  title="Cookie Statement | LazyTools"
  description="LazyTools uses cookies only for anonymous traffic analytics — never for advertising or cross-site tracking, and never involving anything you type into a tool. Here's exactly what that means."
  heading="Cookie Statement"
  updated="July 9, 2026"
>
  <p>
    <strong>LazyTools uses cookies for one purpose: anonymous traffic analytics</strong> — counting page
    views so we know which tools people find useful, the same way most websites evaluate their traffic.
    No advertising cookies, no cross-site tracking, and nothing you type into a tool is ever involved.
  </p>

  <h2>What we use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Analytics cookies.</strong> Used solely to measure aggregate traffic — which pages are visited, roughly where visitors come from, and what device type they use. This tells us which tools to improve. It does not identify you, and it never sees tool inputs or files (those stay on your device and are never transmitted at all).</li>
    <li><strong>Local storage, locally.</strong> Some tools remember your preferences or saved data (like Pomodoro settings or Kanban boards) in your browser's own storage. That data stays on your device, is never transmitted, and you can clear it anytime via your browser settings. This is not a cookie and nothing is sent to us.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What we don't use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No advertising or marketing cookies.</li>
    <li>No cross-site tracking or identifiers that follow you around the web.</li>
    <li>No cookies tied to your tool usage — the content you process never reaches a server in the first place.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Managing cookies</h2>
  <p>
    You can block or delete cookies at any time in your browser settings — every tool on this site keeps
    working exactly the same, because the tools themselves don't depend on cookies at all. Questions?
    <a href="/contact/">Contact us</a>.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
